      "target": {
        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "fix(tools-manager): bound GitHub API JSON response reads",
        "body": "## Summary\n\n`getLatestVersion()` reads the GitHub API release response via `response.json()` without a size cap. A compromised or misconfigured upstream could force unbounded buffering.\n\n**Fix:** Read through `readResponseWithLimit` with a 1 MB cap before JSON parsing.\n\n## Changes\n\n| File | Change |\n|------|--------|\n| `src/agents/utils/tools-manager.ts` | Replace `response.json()` with bounded read + `JSON.parse`; export `getLatestVersion` for testability |\n\n## Real behavior proof\n\n**Behavior addressed**: GitHub API release response is now read with a 1 MB size limit before JSON parsing, preventing unbounded buffering.\n\n**Real environment tested**: Linux (x64, kernel 4.19.112, EL8), Node v24.13.1, vitest 4.1.8\n\n**Exact steps or command run after this patch**:\n\n```bash\nnode scripts/run-vitest.mjs test/agents/utils/tools-manager-proof.test.ts --run\n```\n\n**After-fix evidence**:\n\n```\n RUN  v4.1.8\n\n ✓ bounded read (helper level) > accepts a normal-sized JSON response\n ✓ bounded read (helper level) > rejects an oversized response exceeding 1 MiB\n ✓ getLatestVersion (production path) > accepts a normal GitHub release response\n ✓ getLatestVersion (production path) > rejects an oversized GitHub release response\n\n Test Files  1 passed (1)\n      Tests  4 passed (4)\n```\n\nThe test exercises two layers:\n1. **Helper level**: `readResponseWithLimit` directly — normal payload accepted, oversized rejected\n2. **Production path**: `getLatestVersion()` through a mocked `fetchWithSsrFGuard` — normal GitHub release response accepted (`tag_name: v10.3.0` → resolves to `\"10.3.0\"`), oversized response exceeding 1 MiB rejected with the overflow error. This test would fail if `getLatestVersion()` reverted to `response.json()`.\n\n## Risk checklist\n\nDid user-visible behavior change? (`No`)\n\nDid config, environment, or migration behavior change? (`No`)\n\nDid security, auth, secrets, network, or tool execution behavior change? (`No`)\n\nWhat is the highest-risk area?\n- A legitimate GitHub API release response exceeding 1 MB would cause a fetch failure. GitHub's \"latest release\" endpoint returns ~1 KB in practice.\n\nHow is that risk mitigated?\n- 1 MB cap is ~2000x typical response size\n- Error is a clear `Error` with the limit in the message\n- Same `readResponseWithLimit` pattern already merged in 6+ Alix-007 PRs\n\n## Current review state\n\nWhat is the next action?\n- Maintainer review\n",
